  "summary": "Robin Upward and Mrs. Ariadne Oliver discuss a potential play based on a murder, with Robin suggesting a \"swan song\" and Mrs. Oliver expressing a desire for immediate profit. Robin, frustrated by his script and his mood, suggests they discuss casting and visit the Little Ripple Theatre to discuss a character named Cecil.\n\nHercule Poirot visits Hunter Manor to speak with Dierdre Henderson. He inquires about a \"sugar hammer\"—a copper tool decorated with a bird and colorful stones—to determine if it was originally in the house. Dierdre explains that her mother bought it in Baghdad and it was sold at a charity sale. She specifies the item was sold at the Harvest Festival at the end of September, rather than at Christmas. Poirot notes the discrepancy between this and other information, questioning why Dierdre did not ask why he was inquiring about the tool. He reflects that while Mollie Sampson might be forgetful regarding dates, the slow and clumsy Dierdre should have a more accurate memory.\n\nPoirot later visits Mollie, who informs him that someone called him; she recorded the number in her ration book. Poirot calls the number and reaches Maud Williams at the Brace & Scott Firm. Maud mentions she is calling regarding a house Poirot had previously inquired about. When Poirot brings up the murders of James Bentley and Mrs. McGinty, Maud asks if they can help.",
